      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThese three dissociation steps correspond to the successive loss of protons from the three carboxylic acid groups. The relatively low pKa₁ (~2.9) reflects the strong electron-withdrawing effect of the adjacent hydroxyl and two other carboxylate groups, making the first proton the easiest to remove. The stepwise increase (ΔpKa ≈ 1.3–1.4 per step) is typical for polycarboxylic acids where each successive deprotonation becomes harder due to increasing negative charge on the molecule. These values make citric acid an excellent **buffer** in the pH 3–6 range and explain its widespread use in biological buffers, food chemistry, and as a chelating agent for metal ions.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
